{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Any (strong) (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, ϵ)- two-source extractor is a (strong) classical-proof (n 1, k 1 -log 2 (1/ϵ), n 2, k 2 -log 2 (1/ϵ), m, 3ϵ)-two-source randomness extractor in the Markov model.In the quantum case (where the quantum side information of the adversary is now a quantum system E) one requires I(X: Y |E) = 0 instead of I(X: Y) = 0 and that both sources have conditional min-entropy, i.e.H ∞ (X|E) ≥ k 1 and H ∞ (Y |E) ≥ k 2.Theorem 4 (Quantum-proof in the Markov model, Theorem 2 in [13]).",
    "Any (strong) (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, ϵ)- two-source extractor is a (strong) quantum-proof (n 1, k 1 -log 2 (1/ϵ), n 2, k 2 -log 2 (1/ϵ), m, √ 3ϵ2 m-2)two-source randomness extractor in the Markov model.We now show that quantum-proof seeded extractors that are based on two-universal hash families can be transformed into two-source extractors in the Markov model with minimal penalty (only due to having a second weak source).",
    "This applies to both our Circulant construction and Toeplitz.Corollary 1.",
    "Any (strong) quantum-proof (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2 = n 2, m, ϵ)-seeded extractor based on two- universal hash families is also a (strong) quantum-proof (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, 2 (n 2 -k 2)/2 ϵ)-two-source ex- tractor in the Markov model.",
    "Via Theorem 2, the quantum-proof (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2 = n 2, m, ϵ)-seeded extractor becomes a quantum-proof (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, 2 (n 2 -k 2)/2 ϵ) two-source extractor in the product source model, as it is based on two-universal hash families."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Any (strong) (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, ϵ)- two-source extractor is a (strong) classical-proof (n 1, k 1 -log 2 (1/ϵ), n 2, k 2 -log 2 (1/ϵ), m, 3ϵ)-two-source randomness extractor in the Markov model.In the quantum case (where the quantum side information of the adversary is now a quantum system E) one requires I(X: Y |E) = 0 instead of I(X: Y) = 0 and that both sources have conditional min-entropy, i.e.H ∞ (X|E) ≥ k 1 and H ∞ (Y |E) ≥ k 2.Theorem 4 (Quantum-proof in the Markov model, Theorem 2 in [13])."
